May new homes sales surge in 
US new homes sales for May surged 19.9 percent to their highest level
since March 1994, springing back from a 1.5 percent drop in April, the
Commerce Department reported Thursday.
Most analysts had forecast a modest gain of 1.7 percent. Some 722,000
new homes were sold in May up from 602,000 in April.
New home sales are considered a significant economic indicator as they
usually bring related demand for many big-ticket consumer goods such as
appliances and home furnishings.
Despite May's advance, new home sales for the first five months of 1995
still were 8.5 percent lower thhan the same period a year ago.
The median price for a new home hit 134,900 dollars in April, up from
129,900 a year earlier.
